#: ../../manual/render/blender_render/materials/special_effects/halo.rst:12
msgid ""
"Halo materials renders each of the objects points as glowing dots or a "
"little clouds of light. Although they are not really lights because they "
"do not cast light into the scene like a lamp. These are called *Halos* "
"because you can see them, but they do not have any substance."
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/render/blender_render/materials/special_effects/halo.rst:16
msgid "Halos are rendered with vertex shaders and not with face shaders."
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/render/blender_render/materials/special_effects/halo.rst:18
msgid ""
"This material is useful for simulating special effects, like particle "
"effects or lens flares."
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/render/blender_render/materials/special_effects/halo.rst:22
msgid "Options"
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/render/blender_render/materials/special_effects/halo.rst:27
msgid "Halo panels."
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/render/blender_render/materials/special_effects/halo.rst:30
msgid ""
"To enable *Halos*, press the *Halo* button in the *Material* menu's top "
"panel."
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/render/blender_render/materials/special_effects/halo.rst:32
msgid ""
"As you will see in the 3D View, the mesh faces are no longer rendered. "
"Instead just the vertex is rendered, since that is where each halo will "
"originate. Halos can be hard to find in a crowded scene, so name it well "
"for easy location in :doc:`the outliner </editors/outliner>`."
msgstr ""

